## Relationship with LeetCode 102

| LeetCode 102               | LeetCode 103                               |
| -------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
| Level Order Traversal      | Zigzag Level Order Traversal               |
| Always Left → Right        | Alternate directions                       |
| Queue + BFS                | Queue + BFS                                |
| `ArrayList` for each level | `LinkedList` for efficient front insertion |

The BFS traversal remains exactly the same.

Only the order of inserting values into the current level changes.

---

## Key Learning

* Use **BFS + Queue**.
* Process one level at a time.
* Maintain a direction flag:

```java id="103ah"
boolean leftToRight;
```

* Use:

```java id="103ai"
addLast()
```

for left-to-right traversal.

* Use:

```java id="103aj"
addFirst()
```

for right-to-left traversal.

* Toggle the direction after every level.

---

## Common Mistakes

❌ Forgetting to insert the root into the queue.

Always write:

```java id="103ak"
queue.offer(root);
```

Otherwise, the BFS loop will never start.

---

❌ Forgetting to toggle the direction.

Always write:

```java id="103al"
leftToRight = !leftToRight;
```

after processing each level.

---

❌ Using `ArrayList` with insertion at index `0`.

```java id="103am"
level.add(0, value);
```

This works but takes **O(n)** time for each insertion.

Using `LinkedList` with `addFirst()` is cleaner and more efficient.

---

❌ Forgetting to process exactly one level.

Always store:

```java id="103an"
int size = queue.size();
```

before the `for` loop.

